Another way to think about it is using the multinomial theorem, where you're partitioning the 10 people into three groups of specified sizes. The formula for that is 10! divided by the product of the factorials of the group sizes, and then divided by the factorial of the number of groups of the same size if they're indistinct. So that's why we have 10! / (3!3!4!2!) = 2100.

